\c[4]The Motel Note has been added to Files.
A new development tonight on the tragic accident that occurred in the parking lot of Waystone Public Library earlier this evening.
The female body discovered at the scene has now been identified as that of seventeen-year-old Jacklyn Barton.
According to the teen’s mother, Barton had been walking over to a friend’s house before being struck by an unknown vehicle in front of the library.
Witnesses at Waystone Public Library reported Barton sprinting along the sidewalk in an alleged panic when a black car with New Jersey plates suddenly hit her.
The driver is alleged to have sped through the west end of the parking lot and not make the turn to exit.
This resulted in Barton being directly hit by the car with both being driven through a chain-link fence into the nearby woods.
After this, witnesses reported the driver to have backed up and exit out of the parking lot’s east end. Barton however was killed on impact.
Police currently have an open tip line for any information that can help find the killer of Jacklyn Barton.
She was due to graduate from Waystone Public High School just next month and begin her college career at Suffolk Community College.

"On July 5th, 1999, an employee at Waystone Public Library called local police for a wellness check on the resident of a nearby house. Many patrons of the library had been allegedly reporting a strong “rotting” smell while in the facility’s parking lot. A police visit would uncover the body of Clayton Malthus on an armchair in front of a television."
"It has been determined that Malthus had been deceased for over three weeks with no foul play detected. His cause of death is officially filed as complications from a stroke."
"There is no funeral date set at this time and no comments from his children and grandchildren were given."
"Born in 1912, it’s strange to have lived such a long life with nobody wanting to claim your body or put the money together for any kind of sendoff."
"That’s what happens when all you can provide to the world is bitterness."
"Did he regret his decisions?\! How he was to his sons?\! How he was to his late wife?\! Did he hope the people on the TV would help him somehow?"
"If his children did make a comment to the paper, they would talk about how he didn’t die instantly."
"Sitting in a chair, watching nothing but what you watch every day... His phone was across the room, but he didn’t have the strength to call for help."
"A medical alert button would have saved him, but that would have made Malthus have to confront his pride. He never would have admitted his weakness."
"Even now, he still believes himself to be the smartest person in the room. He is the one who understands how this world works and does not care what evidence goes against him."
"Perhaps in his eyes, death is the best thing to ever happen to him."
